[[Category:History]]

The '''Honduras Foundation for Agricultural Research''' (''Fundación Hondureña de Investigación Agrícola'' or FHIA), (sometimes referred to as Honduras Foundation of Agricultural Research or Honduran Agricultural Research Foundation), is a not-for-profit research facility in [[San Pedro Sula]], [[Cortés (department)|Cortés]], [[Honduras]] which seeks to develop new disease-resistant [[Plant breeding|breeds]] of [[banana]] and [[Plantain (cooking)|plantain]], as well as carrying on research on [[Theobroma cacao|cacao]] and other plant species.

Researchers at FHIA  developed the FHIA-01 [[Goldfinger banana]], which is resistant to a plant disease which threatens the widely cultivated [[Cavendish banana]].<ref>{{cite news |first= |last= |authorlink= |coauthors= |title= A Banana Supreme: 'Goldfinger' is Born |url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=PBPB&p_theme=pbpb&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=0EAF861AA32BA476&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM |work=The Palm Beach Post |publisher= |date=May 16, 1993 |page=1E |accessdate=2008-06-09 }}</ref><ref>[http://archive.idrc.ca/books/reports/V221/banana.html International Development Research Centre (Canada): Breeding a Better Banana] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20051228123251/http://archive.idrc.ca/books/reports/V221/banana.html |date=2005-12-28 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |first= |last= |authorlink= |coauthors= |title= Top banana. (disease-resistant hybrid banana) |url=http://www.accessmylibrary.com/coms2/summary_0286-157378_ITM |work=Discover |publisher= |date=July 1994 |accessdate=2008-06-09 }}</ref><ref>[http://www.fhia.org.hn/dowloads/fhia01.pdf FHIA-01 Goldfinger presentation]{{dead link|date=November 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }} by the FHIA</ref>  The FHIA-03 [[Sweetheart banana]] is already cultivated in Cuba.<ref>[http://www.fhia.org.hn/dowloads/fhia03.pdf FHIA-03 Sweetheart presentation]{{Dead link|date=August 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }} by the FHIA</ref>

It continues the banana research program which the [[United Fruit Company]] originally established in 1958.

FHIA is also a participant in the Integrated Watershed Resources Management Program in Honduras financed by [[USAID]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.usaid.gov/press/releases/2004/pr041130.html
|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20041201070623/http://www.usaid.gov/press/releases/2004/pr041130.html
|dead-url=yes
|archive-date=December 1, 2004
|title=Press Release 2004-107. USAID Launches $23 Million Program in Honduras |accessdate=2008-06-09 |author= |last= |first= |authorlink= |coauthors= |date=December 1, 2004  |year= |month= |work= |publisher=[[USAID]] |pages= |language= |doi= |quote= }}</ref>

